All new files created by installing Microsoft Office 2011 (14.3.6)

This is a list of all the new files which were created by installing Microsoft Office 2011 on my Mac

How it was created

I did the following steps on a new installation of Mac OS X 10.8.4 which had never had Microsoft Office installed on it before:

  1. I quit all applications on my Mac except Finder and iTerm

  2. I saved the output of sudo /usr/bin/find -x / -type f -print to a file “beforeMSoffice.txt”

  3. I installed these files:
    • Microsoft Office 2011 version 14.2.0 (Service Pack 2): X18–08827.dmg
    • Microsoft Office for Mac 2011 14.3.6 Update: Office2011–1436Update_EN-US.dmg
    • Microsoft Error Reporting for Mac 2.2.9 Update: MERP_229.dmg

  4. I launched Microsoft Word, filled in my registration information and anything else it asked me before it offered to create a new document.

  5. I quit Microsoft Word

  6. I re-ran sudo /usr/bin/find -x / -type f -print and saved the output to a file “afterMSoffice.txt”

  7. I ran the Unix diff command on the files “beforeMSoffice.txt” and “afterMSoffice.txt”

  8. I went through the diff output and removed any files which seemed unrelated to the installation process.

  9. The result was approximately 32,500 files which had been added to my system.

  10. I went through the list and grouped them.

“WHY?!?!?!”

  1. I was curious.

  2. I wanted to know not only the obvious files which are created, but the “hidden” ones as well.

  3. If I ever wanted to do a “clean” uninstall of MSOffice, I wanted to have a complete list of all of the files that I would need to remove.

  4. It was a rainy day and I was too brain-fried to do anything else at the moment.

  5. A series of shell scripts did all of the hard work, I just sat there and watched for the most part.

  6. I wanted to see if I could figure out which file(s) were missing from Cannot update Microsoft Office Word 2011 to 14.2.3 on OSX and if that would help solve the problem described there.

  7. Since Microsoft seems to be moving towards having future versions of Office be “online” it looks like Office 2011 is going to be with us* for a long time. (* us = those of us who don’t want to “subscribe” to software)

What I Found: Two ¿encrypted? files

  • /Library/Preferences/.s8chpZHsqJ
  • /Library/Application Support/.jgB9k+J4V3

I opened these files in BBEdit and could not decipher anything about them, nor did I try to.

The filenames vary between the two Macs I have access to, but both of them had “similarly named” files in those paths.

What I found: Three launchd related files

  1. /Library/Preferences/com.microsoft.office.licensing.plist
  2. /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.microsoft.office.licensing.helper.plist
  3. /Library/PrivilegedHelperTools/com.microsoft.office.licensing.helper

The first one seems to be your actual license data, which appears to be encrypted or at least heavily obfuscated.

The second is a launchd plist which tells the third item (the ‘helper’) to run as needed.

Note: if you’re thinking this means that you can just copy these files from one Mac to another, don’t bother. From what I understand the information stored there is ‘coded’ somehow onto the specific computer, so it just won’t work to move them over.

~/Library/Preferences/ByHost/com.microsoft.registrationDB.{long string of letters and numbers here}.plist

A thoroughly un-exciting set of preferences, most of which seemed related to proof-reading tools.
